Both Idea 0 (Gesture-Ink Fusion) and Idea 1 (FluidEdit) propose innovative approaches to combining gesture-enhanced handwriting with contextual language modeling for post-editing machine-translated text. However, when evaluating novelty against the provided related work, key distinctions emerge.

Paper 2 (FELIX) and Paper 5 both address machine translation post-editing using language models, with FELIX focusing on efficient tagging and insertion, and Paper 5 exploring LLM guidance via error annotations—these are relevant but operate in the symbolic/textual domain without multimodal input. Papers 3 and 4 (DUnE and MELO) focus on model editing rather than user-driven text correction, making them less directly related. Paper 1 (FLAME) involves text-to-motion synthesis, which is conceptually inverse to the problem here—generating motion from language, not interpreting motion as linguistic intent.

Idea 0 builds a two-stage system that classifies gestures into discrete primitives before fusing them with text via an LLM. While well-structured and feasible, this approach relies on explicit gesture classification—a paradigm seen in prior HCI systems (e.g., gesture recognizers feeding command inputs). This overlaps somewhat with conventional multimodal pipelines, reducing its novelty despite strong integration with LLMs.

In contrast, Idea 1 (FluidEdit) introduces a *unified neural architecture* that co-processes stylus dynamics, in-air hand gestures, and linguistic context within a cross-modal transformer, avoiding hard-coded gesture segmentation. It treats gesture as a continuous spectrum of intent and allows the LLM to decode "intentional semantics" implicitly through joint embedding. This moves beyond modular pipelines to a truly integrated, end-to-end interpretable motion-language model. The "contextual insertion field" further innovates by dynamically aligning handwritten insertions with syntactic structure using MT error priors—an idea not present in any of the related works.

Crucially, no existing paper combines *continuous, multimodal motion signals* (in-air + contact) with *context-aware language generation* for post-editing, nor reframes gesture as a modality of linguistic expression interpreted alongside text. FluidEdit thus establishes a new paradigm, whereas Gesture-Ink Fusion extends an existing one. Therefore, Idea 1 offers greater conceptual novelty and potential impact.

